1️⃣ Builder Pattern — Definition (Theory)

Builder Pattern is a creational design pattern used to construct complex objects step by step while separating the construction process from the object's representation.

Key idea:

Instead of passing many parameters to a constructor,
we build the object step-by-step using a Builder.
2️⃣ When to Use Builder Pattern

Use Builder Pattern when:

1️⃣ Object has many parameters
2️⃣ Some parameters are optional
3️⃣ Constructors become hard to read
4️⃣ You want immutable objects
5️⃣ You want fluent readable API

Example:

new HttpRequest.Builder()
        .method("POST")
        .url("/users")
        .body(json)
        .timeout(5000)
        .build();

Much better than:

new HttpRequest("POST","/users",null,null,json,5000);
3️⃣ Problems Builder Pattern Solves
1️⃣ Constructor Explosion

Without builder:

User(name, age)
User(name, age, email)
User(name, age, email, phone)
User(name, age, email, phone, address)

This becomes unmanageable.

2️⃣ Parameter Order Confusion
new User("Aditya",25,"Mumbai","999999");

Hard to understand which parameter is what.

Builder solves this.

4️⃣ Key Characteristics of Builder Pattern

Remember these 5 keywords.

Feature	Explanation
Private constructor	Prevent direct object creation
Static Builder class	Responsible for building object
Fluent API	Methods return this
build() method	Final object creation
Validation	Mandatory fields checked in build()
5️⃣ Standard Builder Structure (Important for Interviews)

Typical builder structure:

class Product {

    private Product(){}

    public static class Builder {

        private Product product;

        public Builder(){
            product = new Product();
        }

        public Builder setField(value){
            product.field = value;
            return this;
        }

        public Product build(){
            return product;
        }
    }
}

Flow:

Builder → configure fields → build() → final object
6️⃣ Implementation Rules (Very Important)
Rule 1 — Constructor must be private
private HttpRequest(){}

Prevents:

new HttpRequest()
Rule 2 — Builder is usually static
public static class Builder

So it can be called as:

HttpRequest.Builder
Rule 3 — Builder methods return this

This enables method chaining.

public Builder method(String method){
    request.method = method;
    return this;
}

Usage:

builder.method().url().body()
Rule 4 — build() creates final object
public HttpRequest build(){
    return request;
}
Rule 5 — Validate mandatory fields
if(request.method == null || request.url == null){
    throw new IllegalStateException("Method and URL required");
}
7️⃣ Advantages of Builder Pattern

Remember these 4 advantages.

1️⃣ Readable object creation

builder.method("POST").url("/users")

2️⃣ Avoids constructor explosion

3️⃣ Handles optional parameters easily

4️⃣ Supports immutable objects

8️⃣ Real World Examples

Many real frameworks use Builder Pattern.

Examples:

OkHttp request builder

Apache HttpClient request builder

Lombok @Builder annotation

Spring Framework uses builders internally

Example from OkHttp:

Request request = new Request.Builder()
        .url("https://api.github.com")
        .get()
        .addHeader("Authorization","token")
        .build();
9️⃣ Difference Between Constructor vs Builder
Constructor	Builder
Hard to read	Very readable
Many constructors needed	Single builder
Parameter order issues	No order issue
Hard to manage optional fields	Easy optional fields
🔟 Interview One-Line Summary

If interviewer asks:

"Why Builder Pattern?"

Answer:

Builder Pattern is used to construct complex objects step-by-step, improving readability, avoiding constructor explosion, and handling optional parameters effectively.

⭐ Bonus Interview Insight

Sometimes interviewers ask:

Why not setters instead of builder?

Problem with setters:

User u = new User();
u.setName("Aditya");
u.setAge(25);

Issues:

Object can be partially constructed

Not thread safe

Not immutable

Builder avoids these problems.